<DOC><DOCNO> AP890627-0054 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 0702EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-27 0610</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0630</SECOND><HEAD>Tropical Storm Dumps Rain in Texas; Thunderstorms Over Nation's Middle</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The remnants of Tropical Storm Allison dumped rain today over theGulf Coast, causing streams to jump banks and roads to turn intowaterways. Elsewhere, thunderstorms drenched parts of the Midwest.   Allison hit land in Texas on Monday, bringing more than 9 inchesof rain to Houston in the 12 hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT. The stormheaded north at 3-4 mph, and was downgraded to a depression at 6a.m. EDT, with winds of 35 mph.   Some streets in West Beaumont, Texas, were under 3 feet of water,and 2 feet of water covered a highway near Batson, Texas.   The storm was blamed for the fatal traffic accident of a46-year-old Port Neches man Monday evening, police said. It also wasblamed for the partial collapse of the roof at Northline Mall inHouston and for capsizing a tugboat in Galveston Bay. No seriousinjuries were reported in those incidents.   The storm spawned two tornadoes, both in Galveston County. Onehouse was damaged, but no injuries were reported.   Elsewhere, a solid band of rain and thunderstorms extended fromIllinois across much of Missouri and Kansas to the Texas panhandletoday.   Some areas received heavy rainfall. In the Kansas City area, thestorm flooded streets and downed trees and power lines.   In the Jacksonville, Ill., winds blew trees onto houses and cars.Power was knocked out in half of the city. The thunderstorms movedinto northern Oklahoma today, producing winds of more than 60 mph.   Thunderstorms also occurred over portions of southern Michigan onMonday night. A gust of 60 mph was reported in Gaines, Mich., andthree-quarter-inch hail pelted Detroit.   Scattered thunderstorms also occurred late Monday across the EastCoast states. A lightning bolt zapped the roof of a house inMorgantown, W.Va., leaving a hole more than a foot in diameter,while winds blew off a garage door in Bridgeport, W.Va.   The high temperature in the nation Monday was 108 degrees atBullhead City Ariz., and Palm Springs, Calif.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms oversoutheast Texas and the lower Mississippi Valley; scattered showersand thunderstorms over Florida, and from central Texas acrossOklahoma, the middle Mississippi, Tennessee and Ohio valleys andGreat Lakes region to northern New England; and widely scatteredthunderstorms over portions of the Intermountain region, thenorthern Rockies and western portions of the northern Plains.   Predicted highs: in the 60s and 70s over northern portions of theGreat Lakes, the Pacific Northwest and along the California coast;over 100 degrees for the Rio Grande Valley of southwest Texas to thedesert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s in most of the rest of thecountry.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 43degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 90 degrees at Phoenix, Yuma,Ariz., and Blythe, Calif.   Other reports:   _East: Boston 74 partly cloudy; Buffalo 72 cloudy; Charleston,S.C., 75 fair; Cincinnati 76 foggy; Cleveland 71 cloudy; Detroit 69cloudy; Miami 74 partly cloudy; New York 74 partly cloudy;Philadelphia 77 foggy; Pittsburgh 70 foggy; Portland, Maine, 70cloudy; Washington 78 hazy.   _Central: Bismarck 73 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 73 fair; Denver 60fair; Des Moines 70 cloudy; Indianapolis 75 foggy; Minneapolis-St.Paul 63 partly cloudy; Nashville 76 hazy; New Orleans 78 partlycloudy; St. Louis 70 rain.   _West: Albuquerque 71 fair; Anchorage 58 fair; Las Vegas 84windy; Los Angeles 63 cloudy; Phoenix 90 fair; Salt Lake City 66fair; San Diego 64 fair; San Francisco 56 fair; Seattle 55 cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 70 fair; Toronto 72 cloudy.</TEXT></DOC>